      <hedline>
        <hl1>Busting Crime, or Just Eardrums?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Peter Hogness letter says that neighborhood loudspeakers announcing 'Intruder on the block!' will cause racial tensions (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While working in my office at East 77th Street and Lexington Avenue the other day, I was jolted by a loud alarm warning: ''Intruder on the block! Call the police!''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While working in my office at East 77th Street and Lexington Avenue the other day, I was jolted by a loud alarm warning: ''Intruder on the block! Call the police!''</p>
        <p>Reading ''On Unmean Street, Thumbs Will Work as Crime Busters'' (front page, Sept. 13), I learned that what I had heard was a demonstration of a new block-long security system between Second and Third  Avenues. Yet I work a full block away from the test area, and my window faces an interior courtyard. Surely this Safe-Block system -- developed for private profit -- violates noise regulations.</p>
        <p>And it will have worse effects than interrupting sleep. Unconscious racism often leads to a tightened grip on a purse, or to a crossing of the street to avoid a young black or Latino man. Imagine if you were such a young man, and your mere presence set off a loudspeaker, a police siren and a series of strobe lights. This system will mean less sleep and more racial tension unless it is shut down.</p>
        <p>PETER HOGNESS  Brooklyn, Sept. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
